                {
                    "id" : "introduction",
                    "text" : [ { "text" : "### Introduction\n\nIt is not uncommon to see people doing comparison in a superficial way, without to verify the context. When this happen, we end comparing different situations and classifying them as \"bigger\" or \"smaller\" in a wrong way. Preciselly to avoid these mistakes, in the section **First steps** we wrote the chapter **\"To be or not to be...\"**, dedicated to explain the basis of comparison",
                                 "source" : [ 
                                              { "type": 1,
                                                "uuid": "b5efc8f9-c268-430f-9681-7a43848ee48e",
                                                "text": "History Tracers Team. First steps",
                                                "date" :  {"type" : "gregory", "year" : "2024", "month" : "-1", "day" : "-1" }}
                                 ],
                                 "isTable" : false,
                                 "fill_dates" : null,
                                 "format" : "markdown",
                                 "PostMention": "."
                               },
                                "<p><center><div class=\"first_steps_reflection_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection question_mark\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-brain\"></i></div><div class=\"first_steps_reflection\"><b>Reflection 1: Comparison</b><br /><br />Before to go deeper in the text, let us reflectt about our actual understanding:<br /><br />On this moment, do you consider a specific civilization bigger than other? If so, why do you think this?<br /><br />If you do not consider this, what conduct you to reach this conclusion?</div></div></center></p>"
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id" : "origin",
                    "text" : [ { "text" : "### Are There People Better Than Others?\n\nAs previously discussed, there is a consensus today that our species originated in Africa at least 250,000 years ago and spread across the world",
                                 "source" : [{ "type": 1,
                                               "uuid": "2be849f1-551b-44eb-8fc6-87027dbf8a68",
                                               "text": "Mounier, A., & Mirazón Lahr, M.",
                                               "date": { "type": "gregory", "year": "2019", "month": "-1", "day": "-1" }},
                                             { "type": 1,
                                               "uuid": "cff99ec5-cb25-40ef-b2ee-410a75e73a6e",
                                                "text": "National Geographic Education"},
                                              { "type": 1,
                                                "uuid": "27864fd8-e7f7-4a2f-85c7-e1453e3c5234",
                                                "text": "Abdul Karim Khan",
                                                "date": { "type": "gregory", "year": "2013", "month": "-1", "day": "-1" }},
                                              { "type": 1,
                                                "uuid": "cd61bc64-1358-4bfd-b343-3629facaa3b4",
                                                "text": "González Redondo, Francisco A., 00:41:51",
                                                "date" :  {"type" : "gregory", "year" : "2024", "month" : "-1", "day" : "-1" }},
                                              { "type": 1,
                                                "uuid": "dd34414b-8f55-4e5e-877a-c0e111e871be",
                                                "text": "Wang, Richard J.",
                                                "date" :  {"type" : "gregory", "year" : "2023", "month" : "-1", "day" : "-1" }},
                                              { "type": 1,
                                                "uuid": "867968ea-62d6-4a8a-b3a0-8b82c76d86bf",
                                                "text": "History Tracers Team. Origem",
                                                "date" :  {"type" : "gregory", "year" : "2023", "month" : "-1", "day" : "-1" }}
                                 ],
                                 "isTable" : false,
                                 "fill_dates" : null,
                                 "format" : "markdown",
                                 "PostMention": "."
                               },
                               "<p class=\"desc\"><img id=\"originmigration\" src=\"images/mapswire/mapswire-world-political-white-equal_earth_journey.png\" class=\"imgcenter\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('originmigration', '0%')\" />Figure 1: Map of Human Migration <span id=\"OriginHTMW\"></span></p>",
                               { "text" : "Given that we share the same origin, if a group were considered \"better\" than others to the point of having a \"superior\" culture, this should be reflected in their genetics. However, recent studies on our species show that there are no significant differences to justify the existence of races",
                                 "source" : [ { "type": 1,
                                                "uuid": "2659babf-36dc-480f-a3d9-d37b8c4e1159",
                                                "text": "Templeton A. R.",
                                                "date": { "type": "gregory", "year": "2013", "month": "-1", "day": "-1" } },
                                                { "type": 1,
                                                "uuid": "723b0735-b8c4-4b02-8ce6-6da033ca2454",
                                                "text": "Templeton A. R.",
                                                "date": { "type": "gregory", "year": "2013", "month": "-1", "day": "-1" } }
                                 ],
                                 "isTable" : false,
                                 "fill_dates" : null,
                                 "format" : "markdown",
                                 "PostMention": "."
                               },
                               { "text" : "The lack of genetic evidence to justify such divisions leads us to another reflection",
                                 "source" : null,
                                 "isTable" : false,
                                 "fill_dates" : null,
                                 "format" : "markdown",
                                 "PostMention": ":"
                               },
                               "<p><center><div class=\"first_steps_reflection_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection question_mark\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-brain\"></i></div><div class=\"first_steps_reflection\"><b>Reflection 2: External Factors</b><br /><br />We do not have internal differences that justify the superiority of one group over another.<br /><br />Is this enough? Or are there external factors that still need to be considered?</div></div></center></p>"
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id" : "exercise_v2",
                    "text" : [ 
                        {
                            "question" : "Fatores genéticos mostram que grupos de pessoas são superiores a outros?",
                            "yesNoAnswer" : "No",
                            "additionalInfo" : "Na realidade o que temos é o oposto. As diferentes genéticas de nossa espécie são tão pequenas, que não é possível dizer que haveria pessoas melhores."
                        }
                    ]
